# Git Commit Playbook

When asked to draft a Git commit message:

- Inspect the real repository changes first.
- Check `git status`, staged diff, and unstaged diff when available.
- Suggest splitting the work if unrelated changes are bundled together.
- If the user says not to commit yet, only draft the message.

## Required Format

```text
<type>: <one-line summary>

1. <specific change 1>
2. <specific change 2>
3. <specific change 3>
```

## Required Prefixes

The title must use one of:

- `feat:`
- `fix:`
- `refactor:`
- `docs:`
- `style:`
- `test:`
- `build:`
- `ci:`
- `chore:`
- `perf:`
- `revert:`

## Quality Rules

- The summary line must clearly state what changed.
- The numbered list must describe concrete changes, not generic phrases.
- If `.gitignore` was added or updated, call that out explicitly.
- Prefer 2 to 6 numbered items unless the diff is smaller.
